It’s time for #tongueouttuesday teeth trivia. 
___
How many adult teeth do dogs have? 
—-

Adult dogs typically have 42 teeth while most humans have only 32. 
___
Like us, dogs have two sets of teeth in their lifetime and lose their puppy teeth, also called milk teeth, to make room for their adult teeth. 
___
While human children lose their baby teeth over several years, this loss of milk teeth only takes a couple of weeks!
.
.

The holidays are a time of great joy but pet parents should know things that are toxic to dogs. The last thing anyone wants is a visit to a pet emergency hospital during holiday festivities.
🎄
As we countdown to Christmas, I’ll be sharing some of the dangers of Christmas to dogs. 
🎅
Japanese Yew
This toxic, evergreen shrub is dubbed the “tree of death” by many in the veterinary world. It contains toxins named taxine A and B which can be fatal for people, dogs, cats, or horses ingest them. Commonly found in both the United States and Canada, they are shelter, shade, and ornamental plants. The canine minimum lethal dose is 2.3g leaves/kg.
🎁
Swipe to see what they look like. Let’s stay safe this holiday season and always.

Oh hai! I’m playing peekaboo with my mom from underneath the sheet, but I’m also here to give you another holiday danger to pets. 
🎅

Flames and Lit Candles

We love candles year-round but we make sure they are up high, soy-based, and away from nosy dogs and prying paws.
🎁
Over the past decade or so, we’ve taken comfort in flameless candles like Luminara and other brands that run on a timer, require one small battery, and don’t emit a real flame.
🎄
Unattended fireplaces and outdoor fire pits can cause burns or singed paws. Keep a lit Menorah up high where pets cannot gain access

Baby, Alvin says if your dog is a messy drinker, it’s simply how dogs are made. 
___

Dogs tongue act as a perfect ladle to drink water. Dogs drink water differently when compared to cats. While cats use the tip of the tongue to pull and eventually snap the water in, the dog uses his tongue similar to a ladle to take in water. The whole process happens quickly so that it is hard to notice how the dog shapes his tongue in the form of a ladle; this is something that also makes your dog a messy drinker. 
.

Have you ever wondered what the rainbow pride flag flown at Pride parades means? The original flag few at the Gay Freedom Day Parade in San Francisco in 1978, and was designed by Gilbert Baker. Thirty volunteers hand-dyed and stitched the first two flags for the parade.
___
Baker assigned different meanings to each color. Hot pink represents sexuality. Red represents life. Orange represents healing. Yellow represents sunlight. Green represents nature. Turquoise represents magic and art. Indigo represents serenity and harmony. Violet represents spirit. Stripes were eventually dropped from the design for mass production, resulting in the six-stripe flag that’s popular today.

Today marks two years since our beloved Dexter was taken suddenly from this earth.
♥️
We did everything right: limited vaccines, an amazing diet, plenty of exercise and mental stimulation, regular veterinary checkups, supplements, and lots of love.
♥️

♥️
Dexter died approximately 18 hours after first being suspected of having HSA. How he died is in no way a reflection of how he lived.
♥️
Today and every day, I honor Dexter by remembering how he lived. I want his legacy to be of love and triumph and to inspire others to be kind to dogs. I know he sent Alvin to continue the legacy begun by our Brandy Noel. Each one sends one, that’s my belief.
♥️
“Time is too slow for those who wait, too swift for those who fear, too long for those who grieve, too short for those who rejoice, but for those who love, time is not.” ~Henry van Dyke~
So…..
♥️
I wrote this post in honor of our Dexter and Brandy Noel, who passed the Cocker torch to Sir Alvin. People often ask me the ‘right time’ to get a dog after one passes. 
♥️
You never replace a dog. You expand the love in your heart. Each one sends one.
♥️

Danger alert if you use “smart” products in your home with pets. 
😮
Did you know technology in your home may have silent, unseen effects on cats and dogs?! 
🐾
According to CNET, Dr. Katherine Houpt, an environmental factors expert at Cornell University's College of Veterinary Medicine, says pets routinely respond to sound above the frequencies humans can hear, called ultrasound. "Many dogs are afraid of smoke alarms," she says. "So the dog is going crazy and the owner doesn't know why."
🐶
Tips for 2024: 
🐾
Steps to reduce electronic pollution at home: 
✅Switch off devices at the plug when practical (and save on phantom power draw). 
✅Create a quiet room in the home with no electronics or LED lights.
✅Locate home media equipment in a closet or garage to isolate ultrasound (as well as whine and fan noises you can hear as a bonus). 
✅Shop for LED lights with low flicker ratings
